english:
  title: Record of the Ultimate Joy Pavilion
  author: Cai Shou
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The former County Inspector of Jincan, Magistrate Byeon, came from a noble lineage of illustrious rank. In his youth he served at court, but finding no pleasure in official life, he retired to the eastern slope of Sangju Mountain in Sanyang County, spending his days in the simple joys of fishing and hunting. Yet his dwelling, nestled between broken hills and severed ridges, lacked the openness and spacious serenity he desired. So he sought new ground some three leagues west of his old residence, upon the great river's bedrock, where he cleared the cliffs and raised walls to build forty-some rooms—cool chambers for summer, warm rooms for winter. To the south, he piled stones several fathoms high and constructed a lofty pavilion of three bays, seating thirty or more. Beyond this, he built a tiered tower for a dozen guests. With soaring eaves and lofty beams reaching toward the heavens, with winding railings and horizontal balustrades overlooking the rippling waters, and further east, where the rocks rose high and level like a viewing platform, he carved a terrace. Thus Magistrate Byeon and his country companions gathered here in festive gathering—when guests were many, they sat in the pavilion; when few, they climbed to the tower. As the sun descended and the wind grew cool, when wine had flushed their ears, they ascended the high terrace to gaze afar and let their spirits soar. Truly, in choosing this land and capturing joy, the Magistrate had achieved the ultimate.

    In the year Imjin, I, having served as Censor, was dismissed for remonstrating with the throne. I came to dwell in a villa at Hanseong village, merely ten leagues from Sanyang—so near indeed. My younger brother married the Magistrate's daughter, making us family, and I joined the circle of country companions. One day, sitting with the Magistrate upon the pavilion, we raised our cups and gazed into distance. Crimson cliffs and emerald ridges embraced us before and behind; the clear stream and white stones mirrored left and right. The flowing light and still shadow danced like leaping gold and submerged pearls. Farmers labored in their fields, fishermen cast their lines; red scales leapt upon platters, green sediment floated in our cups. Music swelled, cups circled, joy mounting—we forgot to depart, unaware as the setting sun descended and the bright moon ascended. The Magistrate said, "You have traveled the four directions, climbing every renowned mountain and visiting every celebrated water, every high terrace and soaring tower. Yet here you praise and commend without cease. Now I believe my humble dwelling is neither remote nor crude. Will you not name this place and write its record?"

    I replied: "When a great man moves through the world, entering to sit in the halls of power, emerging to command banners and insignia, with precious ornaments before him and retinue filling the roads—this is what Han Tuizhi called the joy of one who has achieved his ambitions. Gathering mountain herbs and catching river fish, climbing high to gaze afar, standing by flowing waters to compose poetry—this is what Han Tuizhi called the joy of one who has not achieved his ambitions. Yet those who sit in halls of power, though they possess wealth, rank, and precious things, bear heavy burdens and great cares. Chasing reputation and wealth, they cannot enjoy the pleasures of rivers and lakes. And should the sword and axe of punishment pursue them, even their wealth and precious things become unreachable. Those who gather herbs and fish, though simple and austere, often fall into excess or destitution. When hunger and cold press upon their bodies and the mouth worries over food, how can they have leisure to savor the beauty of mountains and streams? These two paths, though called joyful, are not true joy.

    But you—dwelling between river and lake, yet possessing the wealth of princes and nobles, enjoying the pleasures of beauty and music without fear of punishment's sword and axe, with guests and companions filling your seats, playing games or composing poetry, drinking wine or singing songs. Spring flowers and autumn moons, summer rains and winter snows—the four seasons' beauty changes among the mountains and rivers, all entering through your pavilion windows to provide human joy. You lean upon the railing, stroll at leisure, knowing neither favor nor disgrace, hearing neither right nor wrong, daily forgetting yourself with fish and birds upon the rivers and lakes, unbound between heaven and earth. Is this not the ultimate joy?

    Thus I took Zhuangzi's words on ultimate joy to name your pavilion: 'Ultimate Joy.' The tower I called 'Clear Waves,' the terrace 'Boundless Distance'—the pavilion captures its spirit, the tower its waters, the terrace its height.

    Alas, the earth knows no past or present, yet principle knows rise and fall. Once this land lay hidden beneath brambles and thorns, a burrow for foxes and rabbits. Its jagged peaks were known only as mountains, its gentle streams only as water. Who could have known the hidden beauty slumbered here? Then one day, these soaring towers and lofty pavilions rose, facing the river with mountain at their back. With vermillion and green catching sunlight, they illuminate the valleys. Travelers gazing upon them see celestial palaces and immortal temples, moved to praise and wonder. Does not heaven cherish and earth preserve what it has bestowed upon you?

    Yet this too I must say: the mountains' majesty and rivers' flow remain unchanged through ages, while human fortune rises and falls without end. This land lay beneath thorns for countless ages before meeting you, becoming a stage for song and a hall for dance. But who knows that after countless more ages it may not return to being bramble and thorn, where shepherds and woodcutters may tread and sing: "Here once was a certain person who loved to make merry"? Would that not be sorrowful? This is why Meng Chang wept at the sound of Yongmen's zither.

    Thus within ultimate joy dwells ultimate sorrow. Ah, sun and moon fly like shuttles, a hundred years pass like a moment through a crack. Human life is but a journey. We should only drink deeply and care not whether something be ultimate joy or ultimate sorrow, drifting in contentment until we complete our span of years. Would that not itself be ultimate joy? What say you to this?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Han Tuizhi (韓退之) refers to Han Yu, the Tang Dynasty poet and philosopher, whose writings on contentment and ambition are invoked here.
  - key: ''
    value: Zhuangzi's 'Ultimate Joy' (至樂) refers to passages in the Zhuangzi about perfect contentment found in harmony with nature and freedom from artificial constraints.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Meng Chang weeping at Yongmen's zither alludes to a story of Lord Mengchang hearing music that reminded him of the transience of fortune and glory.
  - key: ''
    value: The poem employs the classical motif of Buddhist and Daoist transience to add philosophical depth to what might otherwise be merely a record of an elegant retreat.
